observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

exert effort in the processing of Certificate of Title of the untitled lots in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the legal interest of the LGU and to avoid possible risk of court litigation in the future pursuant to Section 148 of COA Circular 92-386;

consider other legal measures to expedite the possible titling of all lots purchased; 

allocate fund intended for the titling of these lots; and

fully disclose the facts and circumstances regarding the Land account in the Notes to Financial Statement to fairly present the affected accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended management to:
conduct a review of the purposes for which funds were transferred to ensure compliance with memorandum of agreement or other documents prescribing their proper and timely utilization;
identify and analyze the root causes of delays in project implementation through a comprehensive review of plans and applicable processes;
establish monitoring mechanisms to track the utilization of transferred funds and ensure compliance with intended purposes; and
If warranted, request from the source agency the authority to utilize funds for other purposes by providing proper justifications to support its necessity; otherwise, the unutilized amounts should be returned to fully liquidate the transferred funds.

We recommended that management:
continuously ensure the allocation and utilization of LDRRMF pursuant to the policies and guidelines primarily embodied in NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1;
thru the LDRRMC, continuously monitor, coordinate and evaluate PPAs to ensure the completion of the most urgent, needed, appropriate and eligible projects;
continuously comply with pertinent laws, rules and regulations in the recording, utilization and reporting of LDRRMF; and
ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed projects identified during the budget year to optimize the fund's utilization and assure that the goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved.

We recommended that the Local School Board, being the one responsible in the formulation, approval, and utilization of the SEF Budget as provided under RA No. 7160 or the Local Government Code:
sustain its efforts in ensuring that all budgeted projects, programs and activities are optimally and fully implemented;
re-evaluate the PPAs charged under the Continuing Appropriations to determine if they are still needed, procurement and implementation-ready, and supported with available funds. Adjustments should be made as warranted;
from time to time, revisit the revised guidelines on the use of SEF under DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 to ensure a more strategic and efficient formulation and utilization of resources for priority programs and projects; and
for the purpose of hiring teachers chargeable against the SEF, the LSB in each province, city or municipality should utilize the list found in the Registry of Qualified Applicants (RQA).
We recommended that the Municipal Budget Officer provide the different schools, through their district supervisors, information as to their available appropriations for their prompt implementation. In turn, the different schools should maintain a registry of appropriations, obligations and balances to have an updated information that will facilitate their disbursements of funds.

We recommended that Management should be guided by the following steps regarding the processing of Certificate of Title for untitled lots:
Conduct a thorough review of the current status of land ownership for all lots purchased by the LGU and identify which lots are untitled and in need of a Certificate of Title;
Consider engaging legal experts specializing in land titling and real estate law to assist with the process and seek advice on the best legal measures to expedite the titling of all purchased lots;
Coordinate with the relevant government agencies, such as the Land Registration Authority, to expedite the process;
Explore alternative legal measures to expedite the titling process, such as negotiation with sellers or resolution of any legal disputes;
Allocate funds specifically for the titling of untitled lots ensuring that these are sufficient to cover any expenses related to the titling process; and
Monitor the progress of the titling process and the implementation of legal measures and evaluate the effectiveness of the steps taken and make adjustments as necessary.
It is also recommended that the Municipal Accountant include a disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements regarding the Land account by providing details on the status of titles, any pending applications, and the steps being taken to expedite the titling process.

We recommended that management:
advise the concerned offices of the release of the deposits made by suppliers/contractors in accordance with the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and continuously remind concerned claimants to submit their request for refund of their security deposits;
in case of liquidated damages, such amount shall be deducted from any amount due to the contractor or from securities posted by the contractor;
advise the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the deposits on market stalls totaling ₱90,000.00 from Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable account into Customers’ Deposits Payable account; and
strictly comply with existing rules and regulations for accurate financial reporting.

